<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Look for Premier Cru and Grand Cru Burgundy Designations</strong> - The world's best Chardonnays often come from Burgundy's classified vineyards. Premier Cru sites like Meursault Les Perrières or Puligny-Montrachet Les Combettes offer exceptional value compared to Grand Crus, while still delivering the mineral complexity and aging potential that defines truly great Chardonnay. These wines showcase specific terroir characteristics - limestone soils create wines with chalky minerality and remarkable longevity.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Serve at Cellar Temperature, Not Fridge Cold</strong> - Premium Chardonnays should be served at 50-55°F, significantly warmer than typical white wine service. This temperature allows the wine's complex aromatics to fully express themselves - you'll taste the subtle vanilla from French oak, the creamy lactic acid from malolactic fermentation, and delicate fruit nuances that disappear when over-chilled. Remove from refrigerator 30-45 minutes before serving.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Decant Aged White Burgundy and Premium Chardonnay</strong> - Unlike common belief, top Chardonnays benefit from decanting, especially wines over 8-10 years old. White Burgundies often develop sediment and can show reduction (sulfur compounds) that dissipate with air exposure. Decant 30-60 minutes before service to allow the wine to open up and reveal its full aromatic complexity, particularly for producers like Coche-Dury or Raveneau.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Use Burgundy-Style Glasses with Wide Bowls</strong> - The best Chardonnays require glasses designed specifically for great white Burgundy - wide bowls that taper toward the rim concentrate the wine's delicate aromatics while providing enough surface area for proper aeration. Avoid narrow Sauvignon Blanc glasses that compress the wine's complex bouquet and prevent proper appreciation of oak integration and fruit concentration.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Understand the Oak Integration Timeline</strong> - Premium Chardonnays typically need 3-5 years to fully integrate their oak aging. New French oak imparts vanilla, spice, and toasty notes that can dominate young wines. The best producers use 20-30% new oak maximum, allowing 18-24 months for the wood tannins to marry with the fruit. Look for wines where oak supports rather than masks the fruit expression.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Buy from Cool Climate Regions During Warm Vintages</strong> - The finest Chardonnays come from marginal climates where the grape struggles slightly - think Chablis, Russian River Valley, or Tasmania. In warmer vintages, these regions produce Chardonnays with perfect ripeness while retaining crucial acidity. Avoid warm climate Chardonnays from hot years, as they often lack the tension and aging potential that defines greatness.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Age Quality Chardonnay for 5-15 Years</strong> - Unlike most white wines, the best Chardonnays improve dramatically with age. White Burgundy from top producers develops honeyed complexity, mineral depth, and remarkable concentration after 8-12 years. Store bottles on their side in a cool, dark environment at 55-57°F. The wine's acidity preserves freshness while allowing development of tertiary aromas like brioche, hazelnut, and wet stone.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Identify Single-Vineyard Expressions from Top Producers</strong> - Seek out single-vineyard Chardonnays from renowned producers like Aubert, Kistler, or Peter Michael in California, or domaine bottlings from Burgundy producers like Leflaive or Niellon. These wines express specific terroir characteristics - volcanic soils create mineral-driven wines, while clay-limestone produces rounder, more textured styles. Single-vineyard bottlings represent the pinnacle of Chardonnay expression and age magnificently.</li>
